This reel covers a week of #adidasTERREX team camp. It's mostly Grand Canyon shots and wildlife I came across on the trail. This reel fails to capture the multiple game nights, lively dinner debates, and late night conversations. 🌵
.
Mid-week, I dropped my planned run and jumped into a run with @_taymae_ , @emilyhawgood, and @abby.k.hall . Hearing the joys and stresses of their lives in and outside of running while also sharing my own was deeply cathartic. It was my favorite day of camp. 🤗 
.
 A week is never long enough. I'm already looking forward to the next time I cross paths with my #oneteam . ///
.
I'm also seriously regretting not having the time to share more miles with other athletes. @corrinemalcolm , I'm looking at you kid. 🧐😉

Mt Mitchell Heartbreaker 50-miler by @tanawha_adventures exceeded all my expectations. The weather was perfectly imperfect. At mile two, I was Lt. Dan on top of Forrest's boat. Had I cannonballed into a pool, I would have been less wet. The rain stopped around mile 7, leaving the trail a guessing game as to which spot of mud was a friend and which one was feeling feisty wanting to know how strong your ACL was feeling that day.
🌲
The second climb was to the top of Mt. Mitchell (highest peak east of the Mississippi) less than a mile off the summit (mile 24.5) I was moving fast down a steep section of roots when I clipped my foot. Once the shock subsided and I had emptied my tank of swear words, I did an inventory for broken bones. All clear. After realizing I could still run, I eased back into the race. By the time I reached the next aid, due to the amount of blood, it was impossible to see the state of my abrasion. This was a blessing. The possibility of being forced to stop racing for a medical pull was a concern. I tried to get in and out of aids as fast as possible, telling the aid station volunteers who wanted to help me clean up, that I'd take care of my knee at the finish line. Followed by an "I'm sure it is not as bad as it looks". 
🌲
The sun was shining for the last half of the race, my adrenaline was pumping, and I did my best to maintain a consistent pace. 
🌲
I was able to finish 3rd overall and 1st female. 
🌲
After the race, there was a quick trip to the local urgent care, where I received a few stitches. No serious damage. 🙌
🌲
Congrats to everyone who raced! A special thank you to everyone who made this race happen. 
🌲
Extra thanks to @danceswitmountains and @grahamhgt7210 for stopping for 5+ minutes and sacrificing their race placement to make sure I was okay. 
🙏

At @ultratrailsnowdonia, finishing was the priority. I wasn’t going to race 100 miles. I was going to finish 100 miles. Running miles 15-104 without crew added to this challenge. Virtually crew-less, my pack was weighed down with enough gels to last from mile 15-55, then from mile 55 to the finish. Running and not racing meant I would pace myself conservatively, inviting no risk of bonking. 
*
 There was one drop bag allowed at mile 55. Here I took my time. I retaped toes prone to blistering, relubed my feet, put on fresh socks, ate two bowls of soup, and filled my pack to the brim with gels before leaving. I was never pressed for time. I was there for the adventure. It didn’t matter how long the adventure lasted. 
*
Around mile 60, I fell up to my waist in a bog (not a rare occurrence on this course) and snapped my pole. Any other race, I would have stressed about how much time this would cost me on future climbs and descents, but on this day, I didn’t have a single frustrated or negative thought. I collapsed my poles and carried on, happy to be in the Welsh countryside in the sunshine. 
*
Fog and wind played a number on course markings, and the GPX file became my most prized possession. The middle 50 miles I ran with @jonathanvangeuns. Jonathan and I made our way through the course using each other to find our way from flag to flag. There was no sense of panic for lost time, only an absoluteness that I was going to finish. Outside of finishing, I allowed myself one other goal: to finish in the top three and qualify for UTMB. I refused to invest too much energy into this, for fear it would distract me from goal #1. If I finished top three, great! If not, that would be okay too. A goal I never allowed myself to fantasize about in training or during the race was winning. If I caught my brain going down that path, I cut it off at the pass and reminded myself I was going to finish, and that was going to take 100% of my focus. 
*
I remembered who I am. #UTMBbound
*
Finish 📸 @iancorlessphotography

I spent a significant portion of April in the Grand Canyon collecting miles before the heat, and crowds were sure to suffocate the trails. A different species of wildflower painted the Canyon each week. Creek beds that are parched most of their life were full of crisp snow runoff. This was my first time observing the Canyon for weeks at a time, on a daily basis, as it lived around me. I'm still dreaming about long days in April with the sun on my shoulders.

@_taymae_ had been moving well all day, I didn't know how much gas she had left in the tank, but I wanted to find out. I outlined a short-term goal for her: 
.
Make it 10 miles from Green Gate without using a headlamp. 
.
No hesitation, she agreed. 
.
Every few miles, I'd turn to her elated, "Taylor!! Look where you are! It's still daylight!". She'd give me the faintest smile and keep moving. The entire 4 hours I ran with her, she didn't say a single word. I'd check in occasionally, "Have you eaten recently? Are you still drinking?" I'd try to pick up the quietest whisper of a response, then do my best to read her face for a yes or a no, and we'd continue.
.
New goals were a constant: 1-mile to the aid let's push it, 40-minutes until the sun goes down let's get in 3.5 more miles before it's dark, after this aid let's see how fast you can go for 4 miles, 10 minutes until the next aid don't stop running until then, run this hill I know you're in pain but you have to run this climb...everytime she nailed a goal (and she nailed every one), I'd immediately set a new one. She never said,"Okay, let me rest one second" or "hold on, I'm going to walk." Each new goal was a challenge, and the previous one never existed.
.
Between the constant goal setting, I barraged her with sincere flattery, "You're moving so well!" You're a baddass" "You're amazing" "I'm so impressed" "You're fucking strong!" "You're a machine!" "You're an animal." ...you get the idea. 
.
Were the goals too much? Was the cheerleader in me too constant and aggressive? I kept pushing her, trying to find her limits, trying to read her. She matched me every step of the way, never showing the faintest sign of irriation or frustration at  the constantly moving goal posts. 
.
The first picture is the Taylor I ran with; the result of scrapping every corner of her soul to make it to the finish an hour faster than last year.
.
The second picture is her returning to her body after digging to her deepest depths as an athlete. 
.
Taylor's display of tenacity last night will be something that I'll think about forever. 
.
@adidasTERREX
#adidasterrex
.
📸 @iancorlessphotograph

Last weekend, I decided to race the Hellz Bellz 50 miler. 
*
We took an old train to the start line, and then the course led us through a beautiful PNW forest. There was a crystal clear river to lead the way at the beginning and end of the run, along with a stunning waterfall around the 1/2 way point. I lost track of the bridge crossings (50?). Views of Mt Saint Helen's were constant. A warm day and a little under 8,250 ft of gain added to the adventure. 
*
My family had a short drive to the event, so the support system showed up in full force. 
* 
I finished 1st Female and 2nd overall in 8:41:47.
*
 @bivouacracing, the volunteers, and all the local runners whom I had so many great conversations with, thank you for making this weekend so special. 
* 
If Hellz Bellz 50 miler isn't on your bucket list, it should be. 
*
*
*

Letting this moment sink in for the little competitor I used to be and the competitor I am today. 
.
I am racing what is considered to be the world championship of 100 mile running in a few hours. Adidas is my sponsor. I've been living in France for 6 weeks in a house with some of the best athletes in the world. They are my teammates. I am a legit contender for one of the coveted top ten spots. I am a professional athlete. 
.
If my little self could speak up now knowing where I am today, I think she'd have one message: 
.
"Fuck those who don't believe."
.
.

Do I write about how thankful I am…because I am. Do I tell you about all the things that went right, or the areas I can improve upon? Will focusing on this make you think I don’t appreciate what I accomplished? Do I dissect my race from start to finish? This seems exhausting, and a bit boring. Want to hear about my emotions heading to the start line? Or would you rather I lay out hopes and dreams for the future and how I plan on achieving them? Then again…why do I care what the internet thinks? This post is my experience, right? Can’t I tell my truth, leave it at that?
.
Will you hate the monster that lives inside me? She is only happy if she wins. I had the audacity to keep her caged my entire training block, straight through the race. I refused to let her rage. She was furious, scratching the walls of her cage. Be calm, I told her, your time will come. She believes in me more than anyone else. Call her cocky. I need her to succeed. This race is an example of the competitor I am when I do everything I can to protect my mental health. Dreams are curbed. Ambition sedated. Effort controlled. I was a human running this race, not a monster. Get to the start line. Check. Get to the finish line. Check. Don't chance blowing up, not even a little. Revisiting the places I went after my DNF at Grand Raid last winter felt like something I wouldn’t survive if I DNF’d UTMB this year. I risked nothing last weekend. I ran safe. I took notes. I learned. What is left, what would I like to say about my race?
.
1. I am happy with top ten. The woman I was at 25 would have asked me in amazement how I accomplished this feat. She would have been so damn inspired. This is the version of me I've been channeling for the last couple of weeks. She is proud. I am proud.
.
2. I made it to the start line and the finish line. Not a single step was taken for granted.
.
3. I’m giddy with excitement over my potential on this course in the future. One day, I will do a full training block and race UTMB with my monster untethered. She is frothing, waiting patiently to eat this course alive.
.
See you in 2024?
.

Data from 2023:
Women receive 20% of the @hardrock100run field because that is the percentage of applicants who apply that are women. Previous finishers are 10% of the overall applicants. Those 242 runners receive 50% of the field/73 entries. If they had to play by the same rules women are boxed into, there would be 14 postions set aside for this group of mostly men. The  2154 other runners (90% of the applicants) receive 73 entries. 
♀️
No women dropped in the previous finishers category. These women represented 8% of the field.
 
6% of drops were first-time female runners. All first-time female runners represented 12% of the field. 

31% of drops were first-time male runners. All first-time male runners represented 38% of the field. 

63% (!!) of drops came from male previous finishers. All male previous finishers represented 42% of the field. This is the only category where the drop rate drastically overshadowed their representation in the field. Even though they had the highest representation in the field, 
♀️
First-time runners of the race are encouraged via the lottery system to finish at all costs so they can get into the "finisher" lottery pool. Otherwise, they may never get another opportunity to race Hardrock. This is a dangerous mindset to race with.
♀️
Previous finishers are given an easy out if they want to drop since their chances of getting in repeatedly are much higher than a non-finisher. They can do the "Hardrock 50" year after year, with no consequences. Taking up precious entries in the race. 
♀️
When will the "finisher" category be eliminated? It keeps American trail running at a rudimentary level and discourages fresh blood in the sport. 
♀️
Women, you not only have to prove you want to run the race, you need to get as many women as you can to also prove they would like to run. There is a governor set on women. There won't be a single extra spot handed out to us, even though for decades the lottery favored men (source: Hardrock website). We are still being asked to claw our way into the race. Women deserve equal representation at the start line.
♀️
"When you're accustomed to privilege, equality feels like suppression."
♀️
📸@dominiquepowers

2. Find a partner to run with. Your partner can be a person or a pet. Grab a friend’s dog, your neighbor’s dog, or your own. Find a running group, invite your kids or partner to go for a run with you.  Even if they aren’t your speed, or you aren’t theirs, that’s okay. Run at a speed where you can both talk with ease. Once you are comfortable with a partner you can start pushing each other, if that is something you are both interested in. Can’t find anyone to run with? Dial up your mom, best friend or that person you’ve been meaning to call forever. Run or walk at a conversation pace and chat the miles away.
*
   3. Warm-up inside. Winter can make it tough to get in a proper warm-up outside. Your traditional summer warm-up may take twice as long in the winter. Just as the seasons change, so should your warm-up routine. Try warming up on a treadmill before heading out into the cold. This will allow your body to warm up faster, making the beginning of your run more enjoyable outside.
*
4. Listen up. Download a new playlist, audio book, or podcast. Only allow yourself to listen to it while running. This will help you get out the door so you can hear the next song, chapter, or episode. 
*
5. No Goals. Don’t stress about your stats. Have fun on your winter adventure. Stop and take as many pictures as you want. Walk or hike. A run does not need to be a “run”. Training does not have to be about getting faster. It can be about consistency and grabbing miles at any speed necessary.  
*
6.Retail therapy. Buy something new. Put on a new coat, shoes, gloves, or hat. Beyond apparel, maybe you need a new running vest? Possibly there’s a nutrition product you’ve been wanting to try but haven’t. 
*
7. Look your best. You can’t buy something new every run you go on, and the new things lose their shine. If this is where you find yourself, then spend some time dressing up for your run. Do your hair, put on some makeup, spray perfume, wear the running gear that makes you feel sexy, trendy and fast. Get that Instagram post, make your outing fun!

Growing up we always had 4-5 dogs around. They didn't know how to play fetch or how to walk on a leash. They were farm dogs. I loved them, but I always dreamed of a dog that knew basic commands and would not only fetch a tennis ball but drop it at my feet, eager for the next throw. Sable was my first dog as an adult. I answered a "free to good home"  ad on Craigslist. She was perfect out of the box, bringing to life all the dog wishes from childhood I'd forgotten about. 
*
We'd open up the park and close it down, playing fetch for hours, both hoping the strength in her legs would never fade, and my arm would last forever.
*
Sable crewed races and FKT attempts. Before the hair on her chin was more white than black, she was a reliable recovery run partner. 
*
Her adventures and personality quirks would fill a novel, but I'm not in the mood to write a book tonight. 
*
 I debated doing this post. I don't care to spend the time to make it perfect. It is too sad, but some real life might be healthy on Instagram. If you've been a friend of mine or Sable's in real life or online, I wanted to acknowledge she is no longer with us in a traditional sense.
*
On November 30th, Avery and I spent her last day giving her all the treats she desired. I held her as she crossed over to the other side, whispering everything I wanted her to know. Earlier that morning, in the middle of the night, she laid on my chest, and I told her the story of how she came to us and everything she meant to me.
*
Regardless of beliefs, it's comforting to pretend she is playing fetch in a healthy body, waiting to be Avery and I's tour guide as we run through the mountains when we arrive. 🪻

If it's a day without a dog, I'm not interested. 
.
 Zelda was doing frantic laps in her dog run, jumping on the wall, trying to see what was going on in the kennels around her, barking nonstop. I requested to meet her. In a small fenced area, Zelda was wild, hyper beyond control. I wasn't able to pet her. She bolted back and forth in the cage. Barking at anything that moved, not registering the new humans in the pen with her. The dog trainer thought it was best if I came to visit her twice more before adopting her. He wanted to make sure we both knew exactly what we were getting into. 
.
Day 2 I drove the 70 minutes back to @laplatacountyhumanesociety. Zelda, the dog trainer, and I went on a walk together. With the leash on, I was able to pet her. She tolerated me, but I'm not sure if she was loving it. Day 3, we walked with another dog to see how we'd both react. Then, back to the play yard from day one. This time, she let me pet her and even flopped down at my feet for a belly rub. We received the green light, Zelda could come home with me. A puppuccino was in the near future. 
.
The stress caused by people constantly walking by, new dogs coming and going, the chaos of the other dogs talking...Zelda was a ball of anxiety. From the moment I saw her, I knew she was a runner without the ability to run, growing crazy in her confinement. I thought I could help her by giving her all the exercise she could dream of to shake that pent-up energy. I was ready for a project. Then I got her home, and she became a different dog. She is calm, wants to be loved on indefinitely, and I haven't heard her bark once.
.
Many shelters are close to full currently. There are so many little souls hoping for a warm bed and to greet you at the end of the day. Some dogs may not present the most "adoptable" side of themselves in the first 10 minutes or even hour. We can't all be perfect at life changing interviews. Maybe drop by a shelter and see if there's a dog or cat that would fit in, in your home. 
.
If you adopted, I want to see your  little nugget! 🤩
